1. JENKINS PLUGINS (Why?):

Pipeline → Enables pipeline jobs (CI/CD automation)
Maven Integration → Runs Maven commands (build/test)
Git → Connects Jenkins to GitHub
Cucumber Reports → Generates modern test reports

2. JENKINSFILE (What?):
Script that tells Jenkins what to do
Defines stages: Checkout → Build → Test → Report
Lives in  GitHub repo

3. PIPELINE JOB (How?):
Connects Jenkins to GitHub
Monitors repo with Poll SCM (checks for changes every min or 5min or whatever we desire)
Reads Jenkinsfile from repo
Runs stages automatically

4. FLOW:
Code Push → GitHub → Jenkins detects change →
Pulls code → Runs Maven tests → Generates reports →
Shows results in UI

Data Integrity:
"I ensure data integrity by validating across all three layers — UI, API, and database.
 After performing an action in the UI, I verify the response at the API level and confirm the data is accurately stored in the database.
 This end-to-end validation ensures consistency throughout the application.

Flaky Tests / Build Failure:
In my framework I have a Jenkinsfile with stages for checkout, Docker setup, build & test, report generation, and cleanup.
 Our runner class is configured with a rerun plugin that automatically captures failed scenarios and logs them into a file under the target folder —
 this file tells us exactly which scenarios failed. Then the runner class reruns them automatically. If a test consistently fails,
 I quarantine it to prevent it from blocking the build, then investigate and fix it by applying Selenium best practices —
 stable locators, explicit waits, and proper error handling."